06086nam a22007575i 9780822391432DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223914327 a10.1515/97808223914322doi  a(DE-B1597)553794  a(OCoLC)1150217061  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1995b.S728 2008 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.430100aStill Moving :bBetween Cinema and Photography /cJean Ma, Karen Redrobe Beckman. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (323 p.) :b57 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tONE BEYOND REFERENTIALITY -- t1 What's the Point of an Index? or, Faking Photographs -- t2 "The Forgotten Image between Two Shots": Photos, Photograms, and the Essayistic -- tStructural Film: Noise -- tTWO NATION , MEMORY, HISTORY -- t4 An Essay on Calendar -- t5 Photography's Absent Times -- t6 The Idea of Still -- t7 Crash Aesthetics: Amores Perros and the Dream of Cinematic Mobility -- t8 Surplus Memories: From the Slide Show to the Digital Bulletin Board in Jim Mendiola's Speeder Kills -- tTHREE WORKING BETWEEN MEDIA -- t9 Photography's Expanded Field -- t10 Weekend Campus -- t11 Aleph Beat: Wallace Berman between Photography and Film -- t12 Mental Images: The Dramatization of Psychological Disturbance -- t13 Concerning "the Photographic" -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Still Moving noted artists, filmmakers, art historians, and film scholars explore the boundary between cinema and photography. The interconnectedness of the two media has emerged as a critical concern for scholars in the field of cinema studies responding to new media technologies, and for those in the field of art history confronting the ubiquity of film, video, and the projected image in contemporary art practice. Engaging still, moving, and ambiguous images from a wide range of geographical spaces and historical moments, the contributors to this volume address issues of indexicality, medium specificity, and hybridity as they examine how cinema and photography have developed and defined themselves through and against one another.Foregrounding the productive tension between stasis and motion, two terms inherent to cinema and to photography, the contributors trace the shifting contours of the encounter between still and moving images across the realms of narrative and avant-garde film, photography, and installation art. Still Moving suggests that art historians and film scholars must rethink their disciplinary objects and boundaries, and that the question of medium specificity is a necessarily interdisciplinary question. From a variety of perspectives, the contributors take up that challenge, offering new ways to think about what contemporary visual practice is and what it will become.Contributors: George Baker, Rebecca Baron, Karen Beckman, Raymond Bellour, Zoe Beloff,Timothy Corrigan, Nancy Davenport, Atom Egoyan, Rita Gonzalez, Tom Gunning, Louis Kaplan,Jean Ma, Janet Sarbanes, Juan A. Suárez  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aInstallations (Art). 0aMotion pictures. 0aPhotography. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aEgoyan, Atom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorrigan, Timothy1 aBaker, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunning, Tom1 aMa, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSuárez, Juan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeckman, Karen,